## Unlawful Act Punishable by an Authority

The terms [criminal](/Criminal) and [criminals](/Criminals) are often used interchangeably, but for clarity, one might consult the disambiguation pages for [Crime (disambiguation)](/Crime_(disambiguation)), [Criminal (disambiguation)](/Criminal_(disambiguation)), and [Criminals (disambiguation)](/Criminals_(disambiguation)).

In the mundane vernacular, a crime is an act that transgresses the boundaries of what is permitted by a [state](/State_(polity)) or some other governing body, and for which a penalty is prescribed. &#91;1&#93; However, the precise definition of “crime” within contemporary [criminal law](/Criminal_law) is a slippery, elusive thing, devoid of a singular, universally embraced meaning. &#91;2&#93; While specific statutory definitions exist for particular contexts, &#91;3&#93; the prevailing sentiment is that a crime is, fundamentally, a construct of the law itself. It is an act that is declared unlawful by the relevant legal framework. &#91;2&#93; A more encompassing perspective suggests that a crime, or an offence (or criminal offence), is an act that inflicts harm not merely upon an individual, but upon the broader community, society, or the state itself – a sort of public [wrong](/Wrong). Such actions are, by definition, proscribed and subject to punishment. &#91;1&#93; &#91;4&#93;

The inherent wrongness of acts such as [murder](/Murder), [rape](/Rape), and [theft](/Theft) is a notion that resonates across nearly all cultures and societies. &#91;5&#93; Nevertheless, what exactly constitutes a criminal offence is a matter determined by the specific [criminal law](/Criminal_law) of each [jurisdiction](/Jurisdiction). While many legal systems codify these offences in a comprehensive [criminal code](/Criminal_code), others, particularly in [common law](/Common_law_(legal_system)) nations, eschew such a singular legislative compendium.

The state, acting through its [government](/Forms_of_government), wields the formidable power to deprive individuals of their [liberty](/Liberty) for committing certain transgressions. Most modern legal systems mandate strict adherence to specific [procedures](/Criminal_procedure) during investigations and [trials](/Trial). Upon a finding of [guilty](/Guilt_(law)), an offender may face a range of consequences, from [community sentences](/Community_sentence) to, depending on the gravity of the offence, [imprisonment](/Imprisonment), [life imprisonment](/Life_imprisonment), or, in certain jurisdictions, the ultimate penalty of [capital punishment](/Capital_punishment).

Crucially, for an act to be classified as a crime, the physical act itself (the [actus reus](/Actus_reus)) must, with limited exceptions for [strict liability](/Strict_liability), be coupled with the requisite mental state – the intention to commit a criminal act (the [mens rea](/Mens_rea)). &#91;4&#93;

It is important to note that while all crimes are violations of the law, not every violation of the law qualifies as a crime. Breaches of [private law](/Private_law), such as [torts](/Tort) or [breaches of contract](/Breach_of_contract), are typically resolved through [civil procedure](/Civil_procedure) and do not automatically incur state-imposed criminal penalties.

### Definition

The precise definition of crime remains a philosophical quagmire, a subject of ongoing debate rather than settled fact. Different disciplines – law, politics, sociology, psychology – approach it from distinct angles. &#91;6&#93; Crimes can be viewed as wrongs against individuals, against the collective, or against the state itself. &#91;7&#93; The very criminality of an action is context-dependent; acts of violence, while criminal in most circumstances, might be deemed permissible or even laudable in others. &#91;8&#93; Historically, crime was often framed as a manifestation of [evil](/Evil), a perspective that has largely been supplanted by more nuanced, modern criminal theories. &#91;9&#93;

#### Legalism

•
Main article: [Legalism (Western philosophy)](/Legalism_(Western_philosophy))

From a legal and political standpoint, crime is defined by actions that are prohibited by governing authorities and punishable by law. &#91;10&#93; It is intrinsically tied to the [criminal law](/Criminal_law) of a particular [jurisdiction](/Jurisdiction), encompassing all acts subject to its [criminal procedure](/Criminal_procedure). The expansive nature of legal systems means there's no inherent limit to what can be classified as a crime, precluding a single, unifying principle. &#91;11&#93; Legally speaking, crimes are generally considered wrongful acts of sufficient severity to warrant punishments that impinge upon an individual's liberties. &#91;12&#93;

In [English criminal law](/English_criminal_law) and its [common law](/Common_law_(legal_system)) counterparts in the [Commonwealth](/Commonwealth_of_Nations), offenses may be recognized by courts that have evolved over time without direct legislative intervention – these are known as [common law offences](/Common_law_offence). Courts historically employed the concept of [malum in se](/Malum_in_se) (an act wrong in itself) to develop these offenses. &#91;13&#93;

#### Sociology

Sociologically, crime is understood as actions that inflict [harm](/Harm) and violate established [social norms](/Social_norm). &#91;14&#93; Within this framework, crime is viewed as a [social construct](/Social_constructionism), &#91;15&#93; where societal attitudes dictate what is deemed criminal. &#91;16&#93; &#91;17&#93;

In legal systems rooted in [legal moralism](/Legal_moralism), the dominant moral beliefs of a society shape both the legal and social definitions of crime. However, this approach is less prevalent in [liberal democratic](/Liberal_democratic) societies that tend to prioritize [individualism](/Individualism) and [multiculturalism](/Multiculturalism). &#91;18&#93;

[Paternalism](/Paternalism), on the other hand, expands the definition of crime beyond harm to others or society to include harm to the self. &#91;18&#93;

#### Psychology

Psychological perspectives focus on the perpetrator's mental state and their interaction with their environment. &#91;19&#93;

### Criminal Law

•
Main article: [Criminal law](/Criminal_law)

The framework of [criminal law](/Criminal_law) delineates the elements required for an act to be considered a crime:

• [Actus reus](/Actus_reus) – the guilty act.

• [Mens rea](/Mens_rea) – the guilty mind.

• [Causation](/Causation_(law)) – the link between the act and the harm.

• [Concurrence](/Concurrence) – the simultaneous presence of actus reus and mens rea.

The scope of criminal [liability](/Legal_liability) extends to various parties:

• [Accessory](/Accessory_(legal_term)) and [Accomplice](/Aiding_and_abetting).

• [Complicity](/Complicity).

• [Corporate](/Corporate_liability) and [Vicarious](/Vicarious_liability_(criminal)) liability.

• [Mandated reporter](/Mandated_reporter) obligations.

• [Principal](/Principal_(criminal_law)) responsibility.

• [Use of force continuum](/Use_of_force_continuum) considerations.

Offenses are categorized by severity:

• [Felony](/Felony) (or [Indictable offense](/Indictable_offence)).

• [Misdemeanor](/Misdemeanor) (or [Summary offense](/Summary_offence)).

• [Infraction](/Summary_offence) (also known as a violation).

[Inchoate offenses](/Inchoate_offense) deal with preparatory acts:

• [Attempt](/Attempt).

• [Conspiracy](/Criminal_conspiracy).

• [Incitement](/Incitement).

• [Solicitation](/Solicitation).

